{
  "texts": [
    "Building the FOS-graphOur algorithm, described in Fig. 2, analyzes the available information for each paper and creates a weighted, non-directed graph as depicted in Fig.",
    "A vertex (or node) of the graph is a unique fos, and it may be connected to one or more other fos with a weighted edge.",
    "Various fos appear in Fig. 3 like the vertices: x1, x2, x3, etc.An edge connects two fos when they appear in the fos-list of a single paper.",
    "When these two fos appear in more papers, the weight of the edge increases accordingly.",
    "As mentioned before, in the AMiner Citation Network dataset, each paper provides a list of fos in which it belongs; i.e., for a random paper p1 the fos-list may be: [\"Mobile network operator\", \"Wireless network\", \"Mathematical proof\", \"Wireless\", \"Correlation and dependence\"]."
  ]
}